headline: Bank Stocks Recoup Some Losses as Earnings Ease Credit Fears
summary: The S&P Regional Banks Select Industry Index jumped 1.7% Friday, with Zions Bancorp NA and Truist Financial Corp among the top performers.  The modest rebound follows a 6.3% plunge on Thursday, led by Zions and Western Alliance Bancorp after they said they were victims of fraud on loans to funds that invest in distressed commercial mortgages.  The latest crop of earnings helped abate concerns of credit stress spreading across the group following the high-profile bankruptcies of auto lender Tricolor Holdings and car-parts supplier First Brands Group.

summary: As the U.S. stock market experiences modest gains amid ongoing concerns about the banking sector and trade tensions with China, investors are increasingly turning their attention to dividend stocks as a potential source of stability and income. headline: Regional Banks’ Preferred Prices Swing on Credit Losses
summary: The preferred shares of Zions on Thursday slumped by the most since May 2023 to their lowest level in 18 months, while an issue by Western Alliance dropped the most since April 2024.  The shares took back some of those declines Friday morning amid a broader market rally.  Equities on Friday edged mildly higher, helped by solid results from Truist Financial Corp., Regions Financial Corp. and Fifth Third Bancorp.
